narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: I learned a lot about Britain's history, especially during the 17th and 18th centuries. The course provides a framework for looking at American and broader North American and Caribbean history in the context of European colonialism. We also evaluated a lot of primary sources in the course, and I feel that I've gained skills in reading primary source material.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments: The course was well-organized and designed by chronology and theme. Our weekly discussion sections and the materials we read for them were very beneficial and a major strength of the course. Likewise, the lectures were effective and informative. As far as a weakness, while nothing stands out, I feel that the two shorter papers assigned in the course did not service the development of writing skills needed for other courses. A single, longer research paper may have been more beneficial.

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: I would recommend the course to another student, especially to a history major. The course, unlike purely American, European, or South American history courses, puts the regions in context and conversation together. The relationship between European and especially British and American history is studied extensively and a student would gain a lot of understanding of the relationship from this course. The course was weighted fairly between papers, section participation, midterm, and final. No one assignment would make or break a grade. The lectures were interesting and well-delivered.
